Meanwhile, Rey­ nold de Warrenne 2 and the young Robert d'Estoteville,3 with one hundred and forty men-at-arms, had increased the garri­ son at Dive, and when the king arrived at sun-rise received him with shouts of laughter and abuse.
They were also followed by many other troops from Falaise and other castles in the neighbourhood who sought the opportunity of coming to close quarters with the king and his partisans.
Henry, much enraged at finding the snare into which he had fallen, gave orders for an instant assault on the garrison.
The royal troops therefore made a fierce attack, and hurling fire burnt both the fortress and monastery.
Reynold and Robert, brave young knights, and several others, were made prisoners, many also who had taken refuge in the tower of the church were burnt.
Their adherents who were hastening to support them, seeing the vast body of flame, made all the haste they could to return to Falaise.
The victorious king pursued their steps, but no one ventured to sally forth and encounter him.
Evil fell upon them deservedly, according to what the apostle says.
" If any man defile the temple of God, him shall God destroy.”
