THE autumn of this year in Normandy was marked by thunder storms and violent rains as well as battles, and the flames of war, fanned by a variety of circumstances, burst forth openly.
In truth, Robert de Belèsme and William earl of Morton, with many others, obstinately attached them­ selves to Robert the duke, and fearing the king too much to think of submitting to his yoke, resisted him with all their power.
In consequence, Henry having assembled a vast multitude of his adherents, constructed a fort before Tin­ chebrai,1 and stationed in it Thomas de St. Jean,3 with a large body of horse and foot to check the sallies of the garrison.
William, earl of Morton, to whom the place belonged, col­ lected a gallant band of troops, and threw into it a convoy of provisions and other things of which he knew the besieged were in need, in sight of the royal army, and to their great annoyance.
He caused the green corn to be cut in the fields:
